      <content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p><em>Hello friends! This post is here to help give you some ideas about how you might participate in this month&#8217;s Brassicas and Root Vegetables Community Canning Challenge. If you missed the introductory post last week, <a href="https://foodinjars.com/blog/the-community-canning-challenge/">you can find it here</a>. Sign up to participate <a href="https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSd8ZhnX1Wz31QkLhk904wx6ABS-bJNicSxKAp7wEwTeNYfEQg/viewform">using this form</a>, and join me over at <a href="https://foodinjarsfam.substack.com/">Substack</a> (all challenge related posts will be entirely free) or our <a href="https://www.facebook.com/groups/FoodinJarsCommunity">Facebook group</a> for topic discussions.</em></p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img decoding="async" width="1024" height="678" decoding=async data-pin-url="https://foodinjars.com/blog/brassicas-and-root-vegetables-for-the-community-canning-challenge/?tp_image_id=14300" src="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/shredded-cabbage-for-kraut-1024x678.jpg" alt="Metal bowl holding shredded green cabbage " class="wp-image-14300" srcset="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/shredded-cabbage-for-kraut.jpg 1024w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/shredded-cabbage-for-kraut-640x425.jpg 640w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/shredded-cabbage-for-kraut-768x509.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<p>On the food preservation side of the <a href="https://foodinjars.com/blog/the-community-canning-challenge/">Community Canning Challenge</a> this month, we are focusing on brassicas and root vegetables. These storage friendly crops are widely available in the northern hemisphere this time of year, but given their innate sturdiness, should also be within easy reach if you&#8217;re playing along from the southern hemisphere. I really wanted to keep things easy for this first challenge of the year.</p>



<p>Brassica is an official genus designation that includes plants in the cabbage and mustard family. Common representatives of this class include broccoli, cabbage, cauliflower, kohlrabi, rutabaga, and turnip. The category of root vegetable is less official and for our preservation purposes, encompasses things like carrots, parsnips, radishes, and beets. Some root vegetables are members of the brassica family, but not all. </p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="640" height="425" decoding=async data-pin-url="https://foodinjars.com/blog/brassicas-and-root-vegetables-for-the-community-canning-challenge/?tp_image_id=9781" src="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/carrots-in-a-jar.jpg" alt="Pint and a half jar filled with long pickled carrot sticks. " class="wp-image-9781" srcset="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/carrots-in-a-jar.jpg 640w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/carrots-in-a-jar-300x199.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></figure>



<p>These vegetables lend themselves to pickling (either quick or water bathed), fermenting, and pressure canning. Within those categories, there is a wide world of possibilities. </p>



<p>If you&#8217;re leaning towards doing a quick pickle (aka a refrigerator pickle), take a quick read through <a href="https://foodinjars.com/blog/quick-pickles-april-mastery-challenge/">the primer I wrote during the first Mastery Challenge</a>. It&#8217;s got a lot of really useful information and offers up a bunch of suggestions on what you might want to quick pickle. I will have a recipe up tomorrow for Health Salad, which is an East Coast deli staple, and is nothing more that quickly pickled sweet and sour cabbage. I don&#8217;t have a ton of processed pickles that meet the brief on the blog, but here are a list of recipes from the archives that work for what we&#8217;re going for this month. </p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img decoding="async" width="1024" height="678" decoding=async data-pin-url="https://foodinjars.com/blog/brassicas-and-root-vegetables-for-the-community-canning-challenge/?tp_image_id=12380" src="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/prepped-cauliflower-1024x678.jpg" alt="Cauliflower florets in a large glass measuring bowl" class="wp-image-12380" srcset="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/prepped-cauliflower-1024x678.jpg 1024w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/prepped-cauliflower-640x425.jpg 640w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/prepped-cauliflower-768x509.jpg 768w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/prepped-cauliflower.jpg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/mustard-pickles-matty-matheson-a-cookbook/">Mustard Pickles</a> (this is a Matty Matheson recipe. His canning instructions are for open kettle canning, which is NOT advised these days. I make these and refrigerate them.) </li>



<li><a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/spiralized-pickled-golden-beets-with-ginger/">Spiralized Pickled Golden Beets with Ginger</a></li>



<li><a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/quick-pickled-radishes-mastery-challenge/">Quick Pickled Radishes</a></li>



<li><a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/multi-colored-carrot-and-green-radish-pickles/">Multicolored Carrot and Green Radish Pickles</a></li>



<li><a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/quick-pickled-romanesco-broccoli/">Quick Pickled Romanesco Broccoli</a></li>



<li><a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/february-can-jam-pickled-carrots-and-daikon/">Pickled Carrots and Daikon</a></li>



<li><a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/pickled-carrots-and-a-quick-brine-recipe/">Pickled Carrots</a></li>



<li><a href="https://www.fillmorecontainer.com/blog/2014/03/08/quick-pickled-broccoli/">Quick Pickled Broccoli</a> (this one is over on the Fillmore Container blog, but was a recipe I wrote for them). </li>



<li><a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/garlicky-kohlrabi-relish/">Garlicky Kohlrabi Relish</a></li>



<li><a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/csa-cooking-salad-pickles-aka-waste-prevention-pickles/">Waste Prevention Pickles</a> (make these with kale and broccoli stems to ensure every scrape is used!)</li>
</ul>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="640" height="424" decoding=async data-pin-url="https://foodinjars.com/blog/brassicas-and-root-vegetables-for-the-community-canning-challenge/?tp_image_id=10696" src="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/chopped-broccoli.jpg" alt="Broccoli florets and bits of cut stem in a metal mixing bowl" class="wp-image-10696" srcset="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/chopped-broccoli.jpg 640w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/chopped-broccoli-300x199.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></figure>



<p>If you are leaning towards a fermented preserve, here are some more suggestions. </p>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/cabbage-and-carrot-kraut/">Quart Jar Cabbage and Carrot Kraut</a></li>



<li><a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/kimchi-kraut-recipe/">Kimchi Kraut</a></li>



<li><a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/taco-kraut/">Taco Kraut</a></li>



<li><a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/hot-dog-kraut/">Hot Dog Kraut</a></li>



<li><a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/red-cabbage-apple-ginger-kraut/">Red Cabbage, Apple, Ginger Kraut</a></li>



<li><a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/krauty-vampire-slayer-ferment-vegetables/">Krauty the Vampire Slayer</a> (this recipe is from Amanda Feifer&#8217;s excellent book Ferment Your Vegetables. She&#8217;s not really writing about fermentation anymore, but her blog <a href="http://phickle.com/">Phickle</a> remains an EXCEPTIONAL resource. </li>



<li><a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/tiny-white-turnips-fermented/">Tiny White Turnips, Fermented</a></li>



<li><a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/homemade-kimchi/">Homemade Kimchi</a></li>



<li><a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/quick-chopped-cabbage-kimchi-from-korean-home-cooking/">Quick Chopped Cabbage Kimchi</a> (from Korean Home Cooking)</li>
</ul>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="640" height="424" decoding=async data-pin-url="https://foodinjars.com/blog/brassicas-and-root-vegetables-for-the-community-canning-challenge/?tp_image_id=6683" src="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/kohlrabi-in-container.jpg" alt="Three bulbs of kohlrabi in a glass bowl" class="wp-image-6683" srcset="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/kohlrabi-in-container.jpg 640w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/kohlrabi-in-container-300x198.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></figure>



<p>If you don&#8217;t like the things on your list, remember that you don&#8217;t have to use one of my recipes. There are hundreds of food preservation cookbooks out there and many times more recipes on the internet. Just one word of warning. If you are using a new-to-you pickle recipe and you plan on processing it in a boiling water bath canner, make sure that the vinegar isn&#8217;t diluted by more than half and that the recipe contains some salt (without salt, the vinegar struggles to penetrate the vegetables in a timely manner). </p>



<p>I hope that gives you a useful staring place! As always, drop a note in the comments if you have questions. </p>
]]></content:encoded>
