    <item>
      <title>Three Ingredient Fig Jam for Canning</title>
      <link>https://foodinjars.com/recipe/three-ingredient-fig-jam-for-canning/</link>
      <comments>https://foodinjars.com/recipe/three-ingredient-fig-jam-for-canning/#comments</comments>
      <dc:creator><![CDATA[Marisa McClellan]]></dc:creator>
      <pubDate>Thu, 21 Sep 2023 15:03:20 +0000</pubDate>
      <category><![CDATA[jams, jellies, marmalades]]></category>
      <category><![CDATA[For Canning]]></category>
      <category><![CDATA[Three Ingredient Fig Jam]]></category>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">https://foodinjars.com/?post_type=recipe&amp;p=27172</guid>
      <description><![CDATA[This three ingredient fig jam is designed for canning and uses just fresh figs, sugar, and lemon juice. It&#8217;s bright, flavorful, and so easy to make. If you find yourself awash in figs every year, keep this recipe handy! Hello friends! I realize that it has been an absolute age (more than a year!) since [&#8230;]]]></description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p><em>This three ingredient fig jam is designed for canning and uses just fresh figs, sugar, and lemon juice. It&#8217;s bright, flavorful, and so easy to make. If you find yourself awash in figs every year, keep this recipe handy! </em></p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="1024" height="683" decoding=async data-pin-url="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/three-ingredient-fig-jam-for-canning/?tp_image_id=27181" src="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/fig-jam-jars-labeled-horizontal.jpg" alt="Two stacks of jars of fig jam with a blue label that reads 3 ingredient fig jam. " class="wp-image-27181" srcset="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/fig-jam-jars-labeled-horizontal.jpg 1024w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/fig-jam-jars-labeled-horizontal-720x480.jpg 720w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/fig-jam-jars-labeled-horizontal-768x512.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<p>Hello friends! I realize that it has been an absolute age (more than a year!) since I&#8217;ve posted anything new here. I have desperately missed sharing my canning practice with all of you, and while I can&#8217;t promise anything like my old regularity, I very much want to show up here more often. So let&#8217;s dig back in. </p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="1024" height="683" decoding=async data-pin-url="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/three-ingredient-fig-jam-for-canning/?tp_image_id=27182" src="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/figs-close.jpg" alt="Fresh figs in plastic tubs" class="wp-image-27182" srcset="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/figs-close.jpg 1024w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/figs-close-720x480.jpg 720w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/figs-close-768x512.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<p>I&#8217;m kicking my triumphant return off with a recipe for the simplest, easiest three ingredient fig jam. I make this every year thanks to a dear friend who has a massive fig tree in her backyard. Every summer, I eagerly await the moment when she announces that the figs are ready. This season, she gave me more than ten pounds of fresh figs, plus a well-packed gallon bag of frozen figs for later. </p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="768" height="1024" decoding=async data-pin-url="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/three-ingredient-fig-jam-for-canning/?tp_image_id=27184" src="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/macerated-figs.jpg" alt="Fresh figs macerated in sugar in a translucent plastic container. There is a blue spatula sticking out of the container. " class="wp-image-27184" srcset="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/macerated-figs.jpg 768w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/macerated-figs-540x720.jpg 540w" sizes="(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 768px" /></figure>



<p>I spend a couple days gorging myself on them fresh before I get down to the business of making jam. Once I&#8217;m ready to commit them to the canning pot, I portion them out into batches of approximately four pounds. The figs get washed, I trim away any woody stems, and then I cut them into quarters. </p>



<p>The quartered figs get placed in a large container, and then I add two pounds of sugar. If you are starting with a quantity other than four pounds of figs, just make sure to weigh your figs at the start. Then take that weight, divide it in half, and use that amount of sugar. </p>



<p>If you don&#8217;t have a kitchen scale, you can also calculate this 2:1 ratio by volume. Just make sure to pack the chopped figs tightly into a measuring cup and then use half the volume of sugar. </p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="768" height="1024" decoding=async data-pin-url="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/three-ingredient-fig-jam-for-canning/?tp_image_id=27185" src="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/three-lemons-vertical.jpg" alt="Three bright yellow lemons on a marble countertop. " class="wp-image-27185" srcset="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/three-lemons-vertical.jpg 768w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/three-lemons-vertical-540x720.jpg 540w" sizes="(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 768px" /></figure>



<p>Once the figs are quartered and the proper amount of sugar has been added, give the fruit a good stir to fully combine the sugar. Don&#8217;t be tentative, really work the figs and sugar together. We are going to give the figs additional bashing up during the cooking process, so you don&#8217;t need to worry about the fruit. Vigorous stirring is helpful here. </p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="1024" height="768" decoding=async data-pin-url="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/three-ingredient-fig-jam-for-canning/?tp_image_id=27183" src="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/lemon-juice-in-measuring-cup.jpg" alt="Half a cup of freshly squeezed lemon juice in a glass measuring cup, with hollowed out lemons sitting in the foreground. " class="wp-image-27183" srcset="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/lemon-juice-in-measuring-cup.jpg 1024w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/lemon-juice-in-measuring-cup-720x540.jpg 720w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/lemon-juice-in-measuring-cup-768x576.jpg 768w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/lemon-juice-in-measuring-cup-500x375.jpg 500w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<p>I like to let the figs and sugar macerate together in the fridge overnight, but this isn&#8217;t required. You can start cooking the jam as soon as the sugar is dissolved into the fruit. </p>



<p>When you are ready to cook, scrape the fruit and sugar mixture into a large, non-reactive pot. I like a low walled stainless steel soup pot, but enameled cast iron is also a really good option. Remember to stay away from reactive metals like aluminum and bare cast iron when making jam, as they can impart a metallic flavor into your jam. </p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="1024" height="768" decoding=async data-pin-url="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/three-ingredient-fig-jam-for-canning/?tp_image_id=27177" src="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/cooking-fig-jam-on-stove.jpg" alt="Fig jam in a stainless steel pot, boiling away on a turquoise stove. The same blue spatula from earlier is sticking out of the pot. " class="wp-image-27177" srcset="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/cooking-fig-jam-on-stove.jpg 1024w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/cooking-fig-jam-on-stove-720x540.jpg 720w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/cooking-fig-jam-on-stove-768x576.jpg 768w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/cooking-fig-jam-on-stove-500x375.jpg 500w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<p>At this point, you will also add your third and final ingredient. Lemon juice! Figs are relatively low in acid and home canned foods need to have a certain concentration of acid in order to be safe for boiling water bath canning. (<a href="https://foodinjars.com/blog/canning-101-acid-and-ph-in-boiling-water-bath-canning/">You can read more about acid levels in home canning here</a>.) </p>



<p>Typically, bottled lemon juice is used when we are using it to adjust the acidity of a product for safety. However, in the case of fig jam, I find that I prefer the flavor of fresh lemon juice. To account for any variation in the acid content of the fresh lemons, I use double the amount of lemon juice that is indicated by the National Center for Home Food Preservation <a href="https://nchfp.uga.edu/how/can_07/fig_jam.html">in a similar recipe</a>. </p>



<p>I use two tablespoons of fresh lemon juice per pound of figs and find that it gives the jam a really bright flavor without overriding the inherent figginess of the fruit. </p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="1024" height="768" decoding=async data-pin-url="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/three-ingredient-fig-jam-for-canning/?tp_image_id=27178" src="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/fig-jam-droplets.jpg" alt="Drips of fig jam falling off a blue spatula against a off white striped background. " class="wp-image-27178" srcset="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/fig-jam-droplets.jpg 1024w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/fig-jam-droplets-720x540.jpg 720w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/fig-jam-droplets-768x576.jpg 768w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/fig-jam-droplets-500x375.jpg 500w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<p>Once all the ingredients are in the pan, we cook. Turn the heat up to high, get the fruit boiling, and then adjust the heat so that you maintain an active but controlled boil. Stay near the pot and stir every 2-3 minutes so that it doesn&#8217;t start sticking to the bottom of the pan. Because we don&#8217;t use any added pectin in this preserve, we depend on evaporation and the changing consistency of the sugar to achieve set. This means that you can&#8217;t be tentative with the boil. </p>



<p>The time you spend cooking will depend on the width of your pot, the heat of your stove, and how much water the figs contained at the start of cooking. I find that a batch typically takes 25-30 minutes of cooking once it has reached a boil, but it will vary. You will know that it is done when it starts feeling thicker as you stir. The color will go red and rosy. The pieces of fig will start to look a bit translucent. And the overall look will be very glossy. </p>



<p>When the jam is nearly done cooking, I like to run my spatula through the jam and hold it up over the pot. I watch the droplets as they fall and look for thick based, slow moving drops that stretch and are reluctant to leave the spatula. I find that when they meet that criteria, the jam is done. </p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="1024" height="768" decoding=async data-pin-url="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/three-ingredient-fig-jam-for-canning/?tp_image_id=27176" src="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/cooked-fig-jam-in-pot.jpg" alt="The finished fig jam, looking quite rosy, in a stainless steel pot. " class="wp-image-27176" srcset="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/cooked-fig-jam-in-pot.jpg 1024w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/cooked-fig-jam-in-pot-720x540.jpg 720w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/cooked-fig-jam-in-pot-768x576.jpg 768w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/cooked-fig-jam-in-pot-500x375.jpg 500w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<p>Now, while the jam is cooking, I prepare a boiling water bath canner and select enough jars to hold about four pints of jam. A mix of pints, half pints, and quarter pints is fine. The processing time for all of those jars is the same. Please do remember that yields vary and you won&#8217;t hit this exact yield every time you make this jam. Sometimes you might get an extra quarter or half pint. Sometimes it will only yield three pints. This is the nature of jam and it&#8217;s best to adjust your expectations early. </p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="1024" height="768" decoding=async data-pin-url="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/three-ingredient-fig-jam-for-canning/?tp_image_id=27180" src="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/fig-jam-in-jars-overhead.jpg" alt="An overhead shot of eight small jars, all filled with fig jam. The lids aren't on yet, so you can see the color and texture. " class="wp-image-27180" srcset="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/fig-jam-in-jars-overhead.jpg 1024w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/fig-jam-in-jars-overhead-720x540.jpg 720w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/fig-jam-in-jars-overhead-768x576.jpg 768w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/fig-jam-in-jars-overhead-500x375.jpg 500w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<p>Once the jam is finished cooking, funnel it into the prepared jars, leaving about 1/4 inch headspace. Wipe the rims of any sticky drips with a damp paper towel, and apply new lids and clean rings. Tighten the rings just until you feel them grip the jar. If you overtighten the rings, you run the risk of preventing the air from escaping during processing and the lids may buckle as a result. </p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="1024" height="683" decoding=async data-pin-url="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/three-ingredient-fig-jam-for-canning/?tp_image_id=27174" src="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/all-fig-jars-horizontal.jpg" alt="Eight jars of finished fig jam, sitting in three stacks next to a window. " class="wp-image-27174" srcset="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/all-fig-jars-horizontal.jpg 1024w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/all-fig-jars-horizontal-720x480.jpg 720w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/all-fig-jars-horizontal-768x512.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<p>Process the jars in a boiling water bath canner for ten minutes (making sure to <a href="https://foodinjars.com/blog/canning-101-on-adjusting-for-altitude/">adjust for your altitude</a> if you live above 1,000 feet in elevation). When the time is up, turn off the heat, remove the lid and let the jars sit in the cooling water for an additional five minutes. This adding cooling step is something Ball started recommending a handful of years ago to help prevent siphoning and improve the quality of the seal and it is a very effective trick. </p>



<p>Once the jars are done with their resting period, remove them from a canner and set them on a wooden cutting board or folded kitchen towel to cool completely. When jars are cool to the touch, <a href="https://foodinjars.com/blog/how-to-check-that-your-seal-is-good/">check the seals</a>. Sealed jars are shelf stable for at least a year and should be stored in a cool, dark place. Any unsealed jars should be refrigerated and used promptly. </p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="1024" height="683" decoding=async data-pin-url="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/three-ingredient-fig-jam-for-canning/?tp_image_id=27175" src="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/close-on-fig-jam-jars.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-27175" srcset="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/close-on-fig-jam-jars.jpg 1024w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/close-on-fig-jam-jars-720x480.jpg 720w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/close-on-fig-jam-jars-768x512.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<p>Like all fig jams, this one is excellent with cheese and cured meats. It&#8217;s also great in <a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/tartine-day-jam-bars/">jam crumble bars</a>, <a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/preserves-in-action-thumbprint-cookies-from-the-cookiepedia/">thumbprint cookies</a>, rugelach, and <a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/jam-filled-hamantaschen/">hamantaschen</a>. </p>


<div id="wprm-recipe-container-27194" class="wprm-recipe-container" data-recipe-id="27194" data-servings="8"><div class="wprm-recipe wprm-recipe-template-basic"><div class="wprm-container-float-left">
    <div class="wprm-recipe-image wprm-block-image-normal"><img decoding="async" decoding=async style="border-width: 0px;border-style: solid;border-color: #666666;" width="150" height="150" src="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/fig-jam-jars-labeled-horizontal-340x340.jpg" class="attachment-150x150 size-150x150" alt="" srcset="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/fig-jam-jars-labeled-horizontal-340x340.jpg 340w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/fig-jam-jars-labeled-horizontal-500x500.jpg 500w" sizes="(max-width: 150px) 100vw, 150px" data-pin-url="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/three-ingredient-fig-jam-for-canning/?tp_image_id=27181" /></div>
