    <item>
      <title>Strawberry Hibiscus Butter</title>
      <link>https://foodinjars.com/recipe/strawberry-hibiscus-butter/</link>
      <comments>https://foodinjars.com/recipe/strawberry-hibiscus-butter/#comments</comments>
      <dc:creator><![CDATA[Marisa McClellan]]></dc:creator>
      <pubDate>Wed, 08 Jun 2022 14:16:24 +0000</pubDate>
      <category><![CDATA[butters, sauces, curds]]></category>
      <category><![CDATA[butter]]></category>
      <category><![CDATA[strawberry]]></category>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">https://foodinjars.com/?post_type=recipe&amp;p=22092</guid>
      <description><![CDATA[Strawberry hibiscus butter. Smooth and spreadable, this low sugar preserve gets an added boost of color and brightness from the dried hibiscus blossoms. We are smack in the midst of strawberry season here in the Philadelphia region. I picked up a flat on Saturday and the boys and I (they are nearly three years old!) [&#8230;]]]></description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p><em>Strawberry hibiscus butter. Smooth and spreadable, this low sugar preserve gets an added boost of color and brightness from the dried hibiscus blossoms. </em></p>



<figure class="wp-block-image"><img decoding="async" width="1024" height="678" decoding=async data-pin-url="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/strawberry-hibiscus-butter/?tp_image_id=22094" src="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/three-pints-strawberry-hibiscus-butter.jpg" alt="Three pint jars filled with finished strawberry hibiscus butter. " class="wp-image-22094" srcset="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/three-pints-strawberry-hibiscus-butter.jpg 1024w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/three-pints-strawberry-hibiscus-butter-720x477.jpg 720w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/three-pints-strawberry-hibiscus-butter-768x509.jpg 768w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/three-pints-strawberry-hibiscus-butter-735x487.jpg 735w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<p>We are smack in the midst of strawberry season here in the Philadelphia region. I picked up a flat on Saturday and the boys and I (they are nearly three years old!) met some friends out in Bucks County yesterday for a round of picking. I am still trying to find my way back to the blog after a quiet winter and spring, so while I dust off my rusty recipe development skills, I thought it would be nice to share this recipe for strawberry hibiscus butter that I wrote for a 2018 issue of Taproot Magazine.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image"><img decoding="async" width="678" height="1024" decoding=async data-pin-url="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/strawberry-hibiscus-butter/?tp_image_id=22093" src="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/strawberries-and-hibiscus-vertical.jpg" alt="Chopped and sugared strawberries in an enamel pot with a tea ball. " class="wp-image-22093" srcset="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/strawberries-and-hibiscus-vertical.jpg 678w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/strawberries-and-hibiscus-vertical-477x720.jpg 477w" sizes="(max-width: 678px) 100vw, 678px" /></figure>



<p>Strawberries are an essential ingredient in any preserver&#8217;s kitchen and I love working with them. The one downside is that if you want to make a lower sugar jam or butter with strawberries, the finished product often fades in color after a couple months on the shelf. I have found dried hibiscus blooms can help boost the color with their natural hue and bring they also bring a welcome tang to the finished flavor (they are high in an array of acidic compounds). </p>



<figure class="wp-block-image"><img decoding="async" width="1024" height="678" decoding=async data-pin-url="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/strawberry-hibiscus-butter/?tp_image_id=22096" src="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/jar-of-hibiscus-blossoms.jpg" alt="Close up of a jar of dried hibiscus blossoms. " class="wp-image-22096" srcset="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/jar-of-hibiscus-blossoms.jpg 1024w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/jar-of-hibiscus-blossoms-720x477.jpg 720w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/jar-of-hibiscus-blossoms-768x509.jpg 768w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/jar-of-hibiscus-blossoms-735x487.jpg 735w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<p>To make this recipe, you clean, hull, and quarter four pounds of berries. Once they are ready, you add two cups of sugar and 1/2 cup of dried hibiscus blossoms that you&#8217;ve tucked into a large teaball or bundled into a length of cheesecloth. Let the berries macerate at room temperature for an hour and then place the pot on the stove to cook. </p>



<p>Bring the berries to a boil over high heat and then reduce the heat to medium low and simmer for 40 to 45 minutes, until the fruit is tender and quite reduced. When making jams, I typically advise a hot and fast cooking approach, but because the intended outcome here is essentially a thickened puree, this method works best. </p>



<figure class="wp-block-image"><img decoding="async" width="678" height="1024" decoding=async data-pin-url="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/strawberry-hibiscus-butter/?tp_image_id=22095" src="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/three-pints-strawberry-hibiscus-butter-vertical.jpg" alt="Tower of three full jars of strawberry hibiscus butter. " class="wp-image-22095" srcset="https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/three-pints-strawberry-hibiscus-butter-vertical.jpg 678w, https://foodinjars.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/three-pints-strawberry-hibiscus-butter-vertical-477x720.jpg 477w" sizes="(max-width: 678px) 100vw, 678px" /></figure>



<p>Once the berries are completely tender and the volume of liquid is greatly reduced, remove the pot from the heat and puree with an immersion blender. Funnel into clean, hot jars and process (make sure to adjust the processing time if you live above 1,000 feet in elevation). </p>



<p>I like this preserve for kid peanut butter sandwiches, because it&#8217;s not super sugary. It&#8217;s also a good one for filling thumbprint cookies or using as a filling in a rolled bun. </p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Questions about Strawberry Hibiscus Butter</h2>



<p><strong>Can I freeze this butter instead of canning it?</strong> Sure! Just make sure to use straight sided glass jars or clean plastic containers, and leave plenty of headspace to account for expansion. </p>



<p><strong>Can I use a different sweetener in this recipe?</strong> This recipe would work well with either honey or maple syrup (use in the same volume as the sugar). I don&#8217;t recommend using an artificial sweetener like Splenda or monk fruit, as they will become bitter during the long cooking time. </p>



<p><strong>Can I make this with frozen berries?</strong> Yes! Place in the pot frozen and cover with the sugar. Let the sugared berries defrost completely and then proceed. </p>



<p>Looking for more strawberry butters? Try <a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/strawberry-rhubarb-butter-recipe/">Strawberry Rhubarb Butter</a>, <a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/strawberry-maple-butter/">Strawberry Maple Butter</a>, or <a href="https://foodinjars.com/recipe/proudly-homemade-strawberry-honey-butter-from-ball-fresh-preserving/">Strawberry Honey Butter.</a> </p>


